        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nThe patient reports neck pain following a car accident.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports neck pain following a car accident approximately one week ago. He describes hitting the back of his car, resulting in forward movement of his neck and head. He has been experiencing pain since the accident, which is rated as 7/10 in severity. The pain is not constant but worsens with head movement. He has tried ibuprofen, which provided mild relief, approximately 5/10. He denies any swelling or bruising. He reports headaches early on, which have persisted. He has a history of playing football years ago, but denies any prior neck injuries. He did not go to the emergency room after the accident, citing the cost of a $500 visit.\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness to palpation of the cervical soft tissues. Range of motion is limited, particularly with flexion and extension, with pain reported. Rotation is also painful. There is no evidence of fracture on X-ray. Vital signs are within normal limits. No reported visual or hearing disturbances.\nAssessment\nBased on the patient's history and physical examination, the most likely diagnosis is whiplash-associated neck pain, secondary to the recent motor vehicle collision.\nPlan",
